1
00:03:18,140 --> 00:03:22,769
Hello.
My name's Forrest. Forrest Gump.

2
00:03:28,734 --> 00:03:30,610
Do you want a chocolate?

3
00:03:33,071 --> 00:03:37,576
I could eat
about a million and a half of these.

4
00:03:37,701 --> 00:03:42,581
My mama always said
life was like a box of chocolates.

5
00:03:45,083 --> 00:03:48,503
You never know
what you're going to get.

6
00:03:55,093 --> 00:03:57,929
Those must be comfortable shoes.

7
00:03:58,055 --> 00:04:03,018
I bet you could walk all day in shoes
like that and not feel a thing.

8
00:04:05,645 --> 00:04:10,108
- I wish I had shoes like that.
- My feet hurt.

9
00:04:11,652 --> 00:04:14,112
Mama always said there's an awful lot

10
00:04:14,237 --> 00:04:17,491
you can tell about a person
by their shoes.

11
00:04:17,616 --> 00:04:20,994
Where they're going,
where they've been.

12
00:04:28,043 --> 00:04:30,712
I've worn lots of shoes.

13
00:04:32,631 --> 00:04:35,050
I bet if I think about it real hard,

14
00:04:35,175 --> 00:04:38,804
I could remember
my first pair of shoes.

15
00:04:40,847 --> 00:04:43,725
Mama said they'd take me anywhere.

16
00:04:43,975 --> 00:04:46,895
She said they was my magic shoes.

17
00:04:47,020 --> 00:04:50,524
All right, Forrest,
open your eyes now.

18
00:04:57,489 --> 00:04:59,574
Let's take a little walk around.

19
00:05:06,623 --> 00:05:08,583
How do those feel?

20
00:05:11,586 --> 00:05:16,174
His legs are strong, Mrs Gump,
as strong as I've ever seen.

21
00:05:16,299 --> 00:05:20,345
But his back's as
crooked as a politician.

22
00:05:20,470 --> 00:05:24,016
But we're going to straighten him
right up, aren't we, Forrest?

23
00:05:26,643 --> 00:05:30,814
When I was a baby, Mama named me
after the great Civil War hero

24
00:05:30,939 --> 00:05:33,650
General Nathan Bedford Forrest.

25
00:05:33,775 --> 00:05:36,153
She said we was related to him
in some way.

26
00:05:36,278 --> 00:05:41,450
What he did was he started up
this club called the Ku Klux Klan.

27
00:05:41,575 --> 00:05:44,870
They'd all dress up
in their robes and their bed sheets

28
00:05:44,995 --> 00:05:49,499
and act like a bunch
of ghosts or spooks or something.

29
00:05:49,624 --> 00:05:53,462
They'd even put bed sheets
on their horses and ride around.

30
00:05:53,587 --> 00:05:57,716
And anyway, that's how
I got my name, Forrest Gump.

31
00:05:57,841 --> 00:06:01,678
Mama said the Forrest part
was to remind me that sometimes

32
00:06:01,803 --> 00:06:06,308
we all do things that, well,
just don't make no sense.

33
00:06:15,567 --> 00:06:18,278
This way. Hold on.

34
00:06:18,695 --> 00:06:22,240
All right.
What are y'all staring at?

35
00:06:22,366 --> 00:06:26,787
Haven't you ever seen a little boy
with braces on his legs before?

36
00:06:28,080 --> 00:06:31,958
Don't ever let anybody tell you
they're better than you, Forrest.

37
00:06:32,084 --> 00:06:34,503
If God wanted everybody
to be the same,

38
00:06:34,628 --> 00:06:37,339
he'd have given us all
braces on our legs.

39
00:06:37,464 --> 00:06:40,842
Mama always had a way of explaining
things so I could understand them.

40
00:06:42,552 --> 00:06:46,181
We lived about
a quarter mile off Route 17,

41
00:06:46,306 --> 00:06:49,184
about a half mile
from the town of Greenbow, Alabama.

42
00:06:49,309 --> 00:06:52,187
That's in the county of Greenbow.

43
00:06:52,312 --> 00:06:56,733
Our house had been in Mama's family
since her grandpa's grandpa's grandpa

44
00:06:56,858 --> 00:07:00,028
had come across the ocean
about a thousand years ago.

45
00:07:00,153 --> 00:07:04,741
Since it was just me and Mama
and we had all these empty rooms,

46
00:07:04,866 --> 00:07:09,162
Mama decided to let those rooms out,
mostly to people passing through,

47
00:07:09,287 --> 00:07:12,582
Iike from Mobile,
Montgomery, places like that.

48
00:07:12,708 --> 00:07:18,046
That's how me and Mama got money.
Mama was a real smart lady.

49
00:07:18,463 --> 00:07:20,340
Remember what I told you, Forrest.

50
00:07:20,465 --> 00:07:23,760
You're no different
than anybody else is.

51
00:07:25,637 --> 00:07:30,559
Did you hear what I said, Forrest?
You're the same as everybody else.

52
00:07:30,684 --> 00:07:33,061
You are no different.

53
00:07:33,186 --> 00:07:39,693
Your boy's different, Mrs Gump.
His l.Q. Is 75.

54
00:07:39,818 --> 00:07:43,697
Well, we're all different,
Mr Hancock.

55
00:07:47,034 --> 00:07:49,911
She wanted me to have
the finest education,

56
00:07:50,037 --> 00:07:53,582
so she took me to
the Greenbow County Central School.

57
00:07:53,707 --> 00:07:55,834
I met the principal and all.

58
00:07:55,959 --> 00:07:59,254
I want to show you
something, Mrs Gump.

59
00:07:59,379 --> 00:08:06,053
Now, this is normal.
Forrest is right here.

60
00:08:06,928 --> 00:08:11,516
